Security Operations Fundamentals > [T3]: Organizational Chart and SOC Roles

Organizational Chart

Figure - zoom in

The organizational chart visually communicates a company or department's internal structure by detailing roles, responsibilities, and relationships between individuals.

Both big and small organizations use Org charts. The chart helps employees clearly understand their positions and see the big picture. Like any department, the Security Operation Center has its organizational chart. The chart may differ from one organization to another based on factors like organization size, budget, and sector. But usually have major similarities.

 

SOC Team Roles and Responsibilities

Common roles you will see in most SOCs are:

  • SOC Manager: In addition to supervising and leading the entire SOC team and communicating with the upper management, the manager's role is to assess the team, help in hiring, plan and track shifts, train analysts, and improve the SOC performance by continually evaluating a set of SOC performance metrics and KPIs.

  • Level 1 Analysts: The role of Tier 1 analysts is to monitor events/alerts, categorize them, set priorities, and triage alerts. Most Tier 1 analysts are fresh graduates and junior candidates with minimal expertise. They escalate incidents that require some expertise to Level 2 analysts and work with them to acquire new skills.

  • Level 2 Analysts: The role of Tier 2 analysts is to respond to incidents, investigate escalated incidents in a more profound way than Tier 1 analysts and perform containment, remediation, and recovery. 

  • Level 3 Analysts: These analysts are also known as "Subject Matter Experts (SMEs)." They investigate critical incidents and have the knowledge and skills to perform deep analyses. Some of their activities are malware analysis and threat Hunting.

  • Security and system Engineers: The role of a security engineer is to set up and configure security tools and ensure that the SOC infrastructure is performing perfectly. For example, a security engineer sets up the network firewall, configures it, and ensures it provides the necessary information to SOC analysts.
     

Figure 2 - zoom in

Please remember that these roles are just some of the responsibilities in a typical SOC. Others include threat intelligence, vulnerability assessment, digital forensics, etc. But again, it depends on the organization. However, the common thing is that the higher the tier number, the more experienced the analyst. In other words, L3 analysts will be more experienced than L1 analysts in any organization.
